<br>
1) realism is the root of everything. You must have a firm grasp of realism if you're going to venture into stylized art. Not to say that you shouldn't stylize anything until you become a master in realism, but you have to maintain certain boundaries that relate back to realism, so that a stylized character or object still reasonably resembles it's realistic counterpart (examples of that would be taking into account balance, symmetry etc. these can be bent to some extent, but they can't completely be ignored) (yakyakyak, I think you get my point. Your background in anatomy is going to prove very useful for you, here.)<br>
<br>
2) Practice like crazy. A big problem I see with artists who are just beginning is that, instead of tackling the things that they have problems with, they'll deliberately find ways to skirt around doing the hard stuff. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Don't do that</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Take hands, for example: very often you'll see a beginner draw the character with their hands behind their back, in pockets, or even cut off by the edges of the paper. Hey, I'm not exactly pro, either, so I used to do it alot, too. But I remind myself, what am I so afraid of? I should be more afraid of applying to an art school and being turned down for not being able to draw something so essential.<br>
<br>
I think those are the two big things. Learn realism, and practice what you're bad at. Everything else is supplementary to that. As for classes, take whatever you feel will help you with what I mentioned above. Life-drawing classes are a big one, especially. <p>'I like people who acknowledge that they're human without confirming that they're stupid'</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uhyl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/10/02 7:12:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3547.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://personal.jax.bellsouth.net/jax/r/c/rcguerra/Afterrace.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I need help - Seriously</span><hr size=1> OK, seems that I got it: practice practice practice, don't stay stuck with cartoonism, try to learn as realistic as possible (using correct anatomical concepts) with lots of prespective to improve the 3d idea in a 2D world.<br>
<br>
Now I have another question: Seems that I am obcessed with Jim Lee's style. Should I copy some of his images for practice or should I just stay with realistic stuff so my own style can be brought to life?<br>
<br>
Thank you to all the help. It means a lot to me.<br>
