<br>
I think a good idea, maybe, is that if you want to learn how to draw a certain way (there are reasons for it, commercially. Say if you are employed by a company that wants you to reproduce the appearance of something, like a well-known comic character) anyway, I'm getting a bit off track...<br>
<br>
I suggest that if you do study someone else's style, try not to trace. I think it would make sense to work backwards from the finished product. You know, you start with a stick figure, then ball and cone, then finished product. Well try taking the finished product, dissect it into ball and cone and stick figure. know what I mean?<br>
<br>
might want to get a second opinion on that, though, seen as I don't do that much, myself. <p>'I like people who acknowledge that they're human without confirming that they're stupid'</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uazoth30k.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Azoth30k</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/10/02 7:55:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3547.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://homepage.mac.com/azal/giantrobo.jpg height=101 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I need help - Seriously</span><hr size=1> I wouldn't copy his stuff <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> per se</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I would suggest that you look and see how he builds his images. Try and see the forms that he puts under his drawings, how he blocks in his characters, where he puts the lines of action, what the vanishing points are. That sort of stuff. But I would also suggest that you do this with as many other artists as possible. People don't develop styles in a vacuum, you develop a style by absorbing elements of things you see and reworking them into something you like. <br>
<br>
As for classes, well, a general one would be a good place to start. Something that touches on a little of perspective, colour, life, theory, and different media. <br>
<br>
If your goal is just to produce quality art for friends and gifts then I don't think two years is too little time, especially if you practice daily, just so long as it stays fun. <br>
<br>
As for exercises, one of the best ones you can do to help you get what you see in your had onto paper is to pick an object and draw it without looking at the paper and without lifting your pencil. Repeat until the drawing starts to look like the object. Do this with faces too. Get someone to sit in front of you and draw their face without looking at the paper(you can pick up your pencil for this one). Gesture draw too. Try and capture an image on the paper in s little time as possible (this gives it less time to screw up between your brain and your hand <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).  <p><br>"It's a small, off-duty Czechoslovakian traffic warden!"<br>
